description.text: Many years ago, the thumbrest on my clarinet stripped off of my lower joint, so I proceeded to glue the piece back into place. This held up for about a year at a time over 6 years. Now that my little brother has the clarinet and I have a 3D printer, I decided it was time for a more permanent fix.

The model was supposed to have a ring that attaches to the ring around the lower joint, but that broke off as I was removing the support structures. So, I drilled a hole just beyond the tangent of the inner radius. I cut the rest of the attachment ring so it left just two leads on either side of the lower joint. Using these leads for aligning, I fed zip-ties through the drilled hole and tightened the thumb rest onto the lower joint.

NB! Võimalusel võiksid õpilased osaleda ka mudelite valmistamisprotessis (modelleerimises jne).

Step1

In Adobe Illustrator CS6 the top view of the landscape model (incl. contour lines) was made.

Adobe Illustrator CS6'ga joonistati maastikumudeli ülaltvaade (sh horisontaalid).

Step 2

Illustrator file was modelled in Blender 2.76 and then converted into STL file.

Illustratoris loodud faili modelleeriti Blender 2.76's ning valmis mudel konverteeriti STL vormingusse.

Step 3

After printing the model paths (green), river (blue) and exercise points (black) were drawn by marker.

Pärast mudeli printimist joonistati sellele markeriga rajad (roheline), jõgi (sinine) ja ülesande punktid (mustad).

title: Arrow rest for traditional bow (tab style)

description.text:
This is a simple tab-style arrow rest made for traditional bows. When fixed on a side of bow handle the small gap between the rest and bow would allow the arrow fletching to pass through safely, so then you can shoot modern arrows which has plastic/rubber fletchings and stop worrying about fletchings cutting your hand.

To use it, simply print it out of PLA, hold the arrow resting tab and soak the fatter & flatter part into boiling water til soft (should just take a few seconds), then press it against your bow handle while its still soft to make it a perfect fit (wear gloves!), then fix it in position by wrapping with jute/paracord/tape/whatever you prefer.

Feel free to use the Blender file.

The bow featuring in the photos is a snakey curved centershot bow I made from PVC pipe, folloing Backyardbowyer's video tutorials: https://www.youtube.com/user/BackyardBowyer

There are notches in slots to insert connector and then slide it into place. Continue adding frames and connectors in that order as frames cannot be slid into place if connectors are installed first. I like to secure each drawer to wall as I go. Print desired drawers and inserts and install into frames. Inserts hang from notches in drawers. Drawers are designed with stops to keep them from falling out when opened. Tilt up to insert or remove.

Eggbert Egg has gotten himself into a heap of trouble.  He wandered off the trail during a hiking expedition and has fallen and can't get up.  It is your job as part of a rescue team to build a device that will safely transport Eggbert back to safety without causing further injury.
Students will use Tinkercad to design a 3D printable device that can be easily assembled and disassembled to safely transport an egg from one area to another.

Eggbert Egg has gotten himself into a heap of trouble. He wandered off the trail during a hiking expedition and has fallen and can't get up. It is your job as part of a rescue team to build a device that will safely transport Eggbert back to safety without causing further injury. Students will use Tinkercad to design a 3D printable device that can be easily assembled and disassembled to safely transport an egg from one area to another. Student's design must:
  • include 3 or more interlocking pieces.
  • Pieces must be collapsible and able to fit in a ziploc sandwich bag.
  • must be easily and quickly assembled
  • Prevent "victim" from rolling off and out of device
  • allow victim to be "scooped" into device without hands
  • must be lightweight and/or have a low print time

  • must be "low cost" and can include non-printed materials (optional)

    Students will start in Location A (Safe Zone) with their device completely disassembled and placed in a ziploc sandwich bag. Create a path that goes around obstacles (desks, chairs etc) from one area of the room to Location B (Rescue site). Students will follow the path and assemble their device at the Rescue site. Students must get the egg onto their device without touching it and carry the egg on/in the device back to the Safe zone without causing damage to the egg. Teams will be timed from start to finish during the rescue. Students should calculate the cost of their device using a cost grid. The team that successfully transports the egg in a device that meets the criteria with the fastest time and lowest cost wins.
5 days (40-50 minutes/day)

Students should know the Engineering Design Process.   It would also be helpful but not necessary if students had experience using Tinkercad.  If they do not have experience add 40-60 minutes to the duration.
Students will be evaluated on Teamwork, Meeting Design Criteria, Successful completion of the task.  A grading rubric can be used.
Students will learn how to apply the engineering design process to successfully complete a task.

Middle School Science

This lesson is appropriate for grades 6-8 but could be modified for lower or higher grades.

ETS1-3 Analyze data from tests to determine similarities and differences among several design solutions to identify the best characteristics of each that can be combined into a new solution to better meet the criteria for success.
ETS1-4 Develop a model to generate data for iterative testing and modification of a proposed object, tool, or process such that an optimal design can be achieved.

description.text:
This is a 3D Topographical Map of Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada.
Taken from Google Maps data.

It is sized into 16 sections and should fit perfectly onto most 3D printers.
You can easily just scale it down or up depending on your printer. Just make sure that you remember the scale you use when slicing each section.

The images of the printed/painted map are of pieces 1 to 8. Pieces 9 to 16 go directly North (Up) from the painted map.

Order = Left to Right (1-4) and consecutively in the same order above (5-8, etc.)
[13-14-15-16]
[9 - 10-11-12]
[5 - 6 - 7 - 8 ]
[1 - 2 - 3 - 4 ]

Project Name: 3D Topographical Map of Vancouver and the Coastal Mountains

Overview & Background: I live in Vancouver and love every part of it. When people talk about this area they always speak of the mountains and terrain, but really only have post-cards and FLAT maps to look at. This shows how vertical everything is around the city. With the ocean being the lowest parts of the map.

Objectives: Students will get a birds eye view of the area. Seeing and FEELING the differences in terrain height. It's important to know where the flooding areas are and why they flood based on their height. This city and area is known for it's terrain, yet you have to travel very far and into difficult (impossible) areas to see it all. Better than just a computer screen, we can see everything with a full 3D ability.
Audiences: All ages can appreciate it to different degrees. The primary audience is grades 5 and up - based on common Geography lessons.

Subjects: Geography, Sciences (Earth Science), Art - for creating and painting the map.

Skills Learned (Standards): Precision printing, or the pieces will not fit together properly. Possible wood working for mounting the map plates, and painting the map if wanted.

Lesson/Activity: Depending on which parts of the map you would like - print out in PLA for the least number of issues with warping. Since it is a very flat and large base on each piece, PLA will not warp like ABS. Number each piece on the back with a marker to ensure that you do not mix them up, with an arrow showing North or a similar direction for all pieces. The pieces can be mounted with glue to a wall, board, or anything you would like. Another option is to have the pieces kept loose and put together when needed for geography lessons. When discussing the Vancouver and Coastal Mountains, or tectonic plate shifting, or other topics you can use this map.

Duration: Each plate can take from 1 to 4+ hours based on the height of the plate and size of printing scale.

Preparation: You need to have access to or have a 3D printer. There are websites that offer printing services as well, and will ship the pieces to you. Once the pieces are created how they are mounted (or not) is up to you. The rest of the preparation is determined whether the pieces are loose or mounted.

References: google.maps topographical data was used in creating these .stl files.

Rubric & Assessment: Geography - students will have discussed how geography of the Vancouver and local areas has affected the region with: commerce, water level changes, weather, and any other topics that the instructor finds relevant. Students will then use the map to locate where various aspects discussed in the lesson take place, name regions, and other points of interest.

As usual in all my design I’ve splitted all in order to have an easy print of each part, and also an easy mounting after print!

PLEASE PAY ATTENTION: the decouple is NOT SO EASY to create!
You must be good with a soldering iron!!!

IF YOU “FALL IN LOVE” OF THIS DESIGN, PLEASE, REMEMBER THAT IT TAKE TIME TO BE CREATED, DESIGNED AND SHARED… SO “MAYBE” YOU CAN USE THE “TIP DESIGNED” BUTTON ON MY PROFILE!

description.text:
This is based on the Screwless key holder by Marrrs. I create it in Tinkercad. The original was long for North American keys so I wanted to make a shorter version. I didn't like how the zip tie head did not sit flush with the inside and a space was required. I have short zip ties so it required an extra spacer. Now I can place the key ring spacer anywhere in the stack. Also allowed for spacers to have smaller holes or rectangular holes so they don't spin and move around. The zip ties are fed through backwards with this design and protrude slightly on the outer surface.

Modifications:

  1. Modified the shape
    • asymmetric shape to easily identify which way to flip open the key by feel
  2. Shortened over length to 82.5mm
    • because this was rebuilt from scratch I can alter the lengths
  3. Change the way zip ties are installed so that they sit flush with the inside surface.
    • zip ties are installed in reverse to the original version
    • the zip tie ends are tightened through the surface rather than the ends.
  4. Reduced/change the hole shape/size
    • reduced play for key ring attachment
    • spacing washers do not spin

Notes:

  • Zip ties all have different dimensions. The ones I am using are from a dollar store. The head is 4 mm x 5.5 mm x 5.8 mm. Tail is 1 mm x 2.9 mm x 150mm
  • 2 versions included: 1 ziptie and 2 ziptie.

title: Quick 8MM Calibration for X Y Z

description.text:
This part I designed helped me calibrate my cheap printer. Slots and holes are meant for 8mm sized linear rods to fit. Although, use the entire X/Y measurement (30mm * 30mm) to set steps, then rod should fit (very) snug into hole, and rods should slide in and out of slots with minimal resistance. This part utilizes a concept of setting steps to exterior specs to get correctly rationed interior specs.

If needed this part could be flipped to sit on vertical axis to set very accurate Z steps, but may need to be printed with supports.

SET ALL LAYERS TO INTENDED FINISH

for example:
CALIBRATE - single outline, single bottom layer, single top layer.
then
PRINT - single outline, single bottom layer, single top layer.

for example:
CALIBRATE - double outline, double bottom layer, double top layer.
then
PRINT - double outline, double bottom layer, double top layer.

Z height shouldn't be affected this way though

This is the Quantum ORD Bot. It is 3D printer mech platform made from MakerSlide linear bearing. It is extremly ridged and very easy to build. The design can easily be scaled in X,Y and/or Z by simply changing the Makerslide lengths plus belt and leadscrew lengths. This is the mini or 'Quantum' version. The parts other than MakerSlide are either off the shelf standard items or easily fabricate with a laser cutter, 3D printer or CNC router. There is a blog post giving a lot more detail. http://www.buildlog.net/blog/2012/01/the-quantum-ord-bot/ As a reference point, this size uses less than $15 worth of Makerslide extrusion. You also need about $45 worth of MakerSlide wheels, spacers, etc. The Makerslide parts are available at the MakerSlide store. Be aware the rail is released in weekly 'production batches' and sells out very quickly. It is 'restocked' on weekly basis. I have attached the complete 3D design in STEP format plus a DXF of the flat parts. If I can generate enough interest, I may have about 50 sets of parts fabricated and offer kits. That would be for the mechatronics platform only. The extruder, electronics, etc would not be included. Why spend $200 for a set of printed parts when you can have everything you see here, including motors, belts, pulleys for about $200? Planned changes.
  • I plan to change the crossbar handle thing to an extrusion to make it more scalable.
  • The 'quantum' design currently uses NEMA14 motors. I plan to tweak the parts to be compatible with NEMA17. This just adds a second pattern to some parts.
Use the DXF or 3D STEP file to create the parts with a laser cutter, 3D Printer or CNC router.

title: HammerShot PETG-Ready Cylinder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Are you a Nerf Internet Community diehard who uses Stefans, Slugs, domes, or other homemade darts? Do you like awesome sidearms and/or dual-wielding? Print this replacement cylinder and make a HammerShot ready for the most competitive NIC wars.

This replacement cylinder has five slots to hold PETG tubing, which can be purchased from industrial and plastics suppliers. The tubing is more consistent and airtight than 3D-printed barrels. Printing this cylinder from ABS or PLA, then combining it with commercial PETG barrels, lets use your preferred printer and filament without sacrificing battlefield performance.

To clarify, this model requires PETG tubing to be glued in after printing. You can print the cylinder with ABS, PLA, or any other material. Visit a Nerf Internet Community site like nerfhaven.com to find a supplier.

This cylinder uses the stock indexing mechanism (ratchet) for a more robust, longer-lasting design. The longer barrels and open airway improve ranges over stock, and the PETG tubing is more reliably airtight and has lower friction than 3D-printed barrels.

This mod is fully compatible with spring, trigger, hammer, and plunger modifications. It hasn't been tested against any cosmetic modifications.

To install:

  • Print the cylinder and install PETG tubing. You can apply a bead of silicone sealant or Goop to the tubing for a tighter seal.
  • Disassemble your HammerShot.
  • Use a claw hammer or pry bar to remove the endcap from the spindle rod.
  • Pry the spindle out of the cylinder.
  • Remove the ratchet mechanism and ratchet spring from the cylinder.
  • Install the ratchet spring, then the ratchet mechanism, in the replacement cylinder. Be careful to align the indexing bits on the ratchet mechanism with the notches on the cylinder.
  • Push the spindle through the ratchet mechanism and cylinder.
  • Replace the endcap.
  • Install the new cylinder assembly in the HammerShot and test.

FAQ:

  • Can I just install this without the tubing? No. This replacement cylinder is not airtight.
  • What is PETG? It's a thin, rigid plastic tubing used by Nerf diehards, because it fits homemade darts.
  • Will I be able to use the modded blaster with stock darts? Yes, with a minor range increase. However, 1/2" PETG is wider than the stock barrels. Stock Streamlines and other darts will fit loosely and fall out.
  • How cool will I look with HammerShots akimbo? Damn cool, until you try to reload.
  • Can I rear-load darts? No. The outlet of the HammerShot's plunger tube is too narrow. If I make the air inlets wide enough to rear-load, the blaster won't seal properly.
  • Where can I get PETG? From suppliers like McMaster-Carr and specialty plastic suppliers. Search a Nerf Internet Community site like nerfhaven.com for definitive information.
  • Can't you just tell me where to buy PETG? No. If you're using Nerf Internet Community blasters, I want you to be part of the NIC.
  • Is the blaster safe to dry-fire? Yes. The HammerShot's plunger head is made of soft vinyl and survives dry-firing well.
  • Does it seal well? Yes. The HammerShot's plunger tube has a thick, soft neoprene skirt and seals well. I recommend printing with a raft - the contact surface doesn't need to be smooth, but it does need to be flat.
  • That shot didn't hit me! You're cheating! Barrel tap! That hit you!
  • Can I print this with PLA? Sure. Mine is. Avoid using the blaster during cold weather, which makes PLA brittle.

description.text:
Before trying to print Nylon filaments with my Dremel Idea Builder I wanted to make sure that I get as much of the potentially toxic fumes out of my working area as soon as possible.
The solution should be rather cheap and easy to implement.

Shopping list

=> wooden base plate 35.5 x 50 cm
=> distance holder / vibration damper between base plate and printer case (I used two layers of PE foam string with 10mm diameter: http://www.hornbach.de/shop/Fugenfuellprofil-10mm-1-PAK5x1m/8605484/artikel.html)
=> air ventilation unit for 150mm pipe diameter (I used a 230V AC version for toilet / bath ventilation purposes - http://www.hornbach.de/shop/Rohreinschubventilator-Rotheigner-Air-Tube-150/8626716/artikel.html)
=> attachment unit for ventilator to base plate
=> PVC ventilation duct hose stretchable (or similar)
=> electric cable & plug
=> on/off switch
=> if the air ventilation unit does not come with build in speed regulation there are respective Power Control units available (e.g. I've used https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00NQBZUJQ/)

All in all i ended up with approx. 110 EUR costs

This is a calibration print designed to test the rod length settings, and compensate for wall thickness errors. To print: print with 1-2 perimeters, and no fill/top/bottom (they're not needed). DO NOT REMOVE FROM THE BED (or make a note which way the arm with the circle faces) as it matters which arms correspond to each tower. To use: measure the distance from the outside of one of the squares to the opposite side of the center hexagon. Also measure the outside of that same square to the inside of that same square. The difference between those two should be 100 mm (i.e. if you measure the square at 10.3 mm, the overall distance should be 110.3 mm). The distance from one square to the opposite square, measuring the outsides, should be 200 mm.

The measurements of the arms closest to and furthest from each tower, can be used to verify the rod length for that tower.

I printed this with PLA and it fits around the PSU with a little play, but be aware of the shrinkage of your filament.

OpenSCAD code is available on Github.
